display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:em>smooth</fr:em> if the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_n]]></fr:tex> are smooth;
    it is said to be <fr:em>proper</fr:em> if the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_n]]></fr:tex> are compact.
    A <fr:em>normal crossing divisor</fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[D_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, assumed to be smooth, is a family <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[D_n\subset  X_n]]></fr:tex> of normal crossing divisors (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.2"
href="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.2.xml"
number="3.1.2" />) such that the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U_n=X_n\setminus  D_n]]></fr:tex> form a simplicial subscheme <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
    This definition is justified by the following lemma.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
